<H3> <TI>   Hata Comments on Discrimination Against Koreans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Comments on Discrimination Against Koreans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406090794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0857 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
said Tuesday [14 June] the government will deal with 
discrimination against Koreans living in Japan in the wake of 
reported assaults on students going to pro-Pyongyang schools. 
"That (Korean) children have been hurt is intolerable," Hata 
told a session of the House of Councilors Budget Committee. 
Hata said he will urge all ministries and agencies to think 
about appeals to stop such racial discrimination. 
  In recent weeks there have been frequent reports of Korean 
students being subjected to abusive language by Japanese and in 
some cases of the ethnic uniforms of female Korean students even 
being ripped to shreds. Police suspect that there must be a 
sense of discrimination against pro-Pyongyang Koreans behind the 
scenes amid the international tension over North Korea's 
suspected nuclear arms development program. 
  National Public Safety Commission Chief Hajime Ishii and 
Justice Minister Hiroshi Nakai told the same committee session 
that the situation is "regrettable," adding that the government 
will intensify investigations and improve measures to protect 
foreigners' human rights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

