<H3> <TI>   DPRK's NPT Pullout Said To Depend on U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK's NPT Pullout Said To Depend on U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506160094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1511 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- North Korea's possible 
withdrawal from the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) 
depends on moves taken by the United States, a senior official 
of Pyongyang's ruling party was quoted as saying Wednesday. 
  Kim Yong-gon [name as received], deputy head of the Korean 
Workers Party's International Department, brushed aside 
allegations of North Korea's nuclear arms development during a 
meeting in Pyongyang with two visiting House of Representatives 
members of the main opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), 
LDP officials said. Kim called the alleged nuclear arms 
development a fabrication and a plot aimed at isolating North 
Korea from the international community, the officials said, 
quoting reports received from the two, including former Defense 
Agency Chief Taku Yamasaki. 
  In response to the LDP members' call for North Korea to stay 
in the NPT regime, Kim said its withdrawal "depends on what 
action the U.S. will take," the officials said. He also said 
Pyongyang "will counter dialogue with dialogue, sanctions with 
reprisals, and war with war," they added. 

</TEXT>

