<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Accepts Sanctions `in Principle' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Accepts Sanctions `in Principle' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506130594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1259 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa said Wednesday Japan will accept in principle draft 
sanctions against North Korea mapped out by the United States. 
  The proposed sanctions are on the whole close to what Japan 
thinks proper to cope with the nuclear crisis, Kakizawa said 
after an emergency meeting of government leaders called to 
discuss the issue. 
  The U.S. plans to propose a sanctions resolution to the UN 
Security Council over the nuclear standoff triggered by North 
Korea's refusal to allow international inspections of its 
suspected nuclear arms development program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29045 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas115_a_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-115 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Proposal `Close' to Tokyo's Ideas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Proposal `Close' to Tokyo's Ideas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506153894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1523 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- Japan will inform the 
United States that it will accept in principle its draft 
sanctions against North Korea to be presented to the U.N. 
Security Council over the nuclear crisis, government officials 
said. 
  "On the whole, (the proposed sanctions) are close to what 
Japan thinks proper, so we will in principle accept them," 
Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa told reporters after attending an 
emergency meeting of government leaders on the nuclear standoff. 
  The United States plans to propose a sanctions resolution to 
the Security Council over the nuclear standoff triggered by 
North Korea's refusal to allow International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) checks of its suspected nuclear arms development 
program. 
  Japanese U.N. Ambassador Hisashi Owada will inform his U.S. 
counterpart of Japan's acceptance of the draft early Thursday 
[16 June], the officials said. 
  They declined to disclose, however, if the draft sanctions 
would include an order to halt bank remittances of cash from 
pro-Pyongyang Koreans living in Japan to North Korea. Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai only said the sanctions would 
"not be easy" for North Korea. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata discussed the nuclear crisis 
with 
Kakizawa, Kumagai and senior foreign ministry officers in the 
meeting at his official residence. In the meeting, Hata said 
there are three principles on which Japan should act in dealing 
with the sanctions, the officials said. These are imposing 
sanctions step by step as a means of maintaining dialogue with 
the North, keeping close contact with the U.S., South Korea and 
other permanent Security Council members, and doing whatever is 
possible within the framework of the Constitution. 
  Also present at the emergency talks were Vice Foreign 
Minister Kunihiko Saito and the ministry's director-general of 
the Foreign Policy Bureau, Shunji Yanai. The Foreign Ministry 
officials were quoted as saying there is a feeling even among 
the 10 nonpermanent Security Council members that the nuclear 
issue cannot be left as it is. 
  The Security Council consists of five permanent members -- 
Britain, China, France, Russia and the U.S. -- as well as the 10 
nonpermanent members. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

