<H3> <TI>   Kakizawa Considers Visit to U.S. for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakizawa Considers Visit to U.S. for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506035994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0325 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506035994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa may visit the United States possibly later this month 
or early July for talks with U.S. officials, government sources 
said Wednesday [15 June]. 
  Kakizawa is considering making the trip after the budget for 
fiscal 1994 passes the Diet around June 23 or 24, the sources 
said. 
  He is expected to meet Secretary of State Warren Christopher 
and U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor. 
  Kantor has reportedly been urging Kakizawa to visit the U.S. 
to promote talks on bilateral trade framework negotiations. 
  Japan and the U.S. agreed last month to resume the trade 
framework talks, which broke down in February when President 
Bill Clinton and then Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa met in 
Washington. 
  The two countries have been holding working-level talks 
since 
then and are scheduled to hold vice ministerial talks in Tokyo 
on June 22 and 23 between Deputy U.S. Trade Representative 
Charlene Barshefsky and Deputy Foreign Minister Sadayuki Hayashi. 
  Kakizawa is also likely to discuss North Korea's alleged 
nuclear development with Christopher along with measures to be 
taken by the United Nations, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

