<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, U.S. `Narrowing Differences' on Autos </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo, U.S. `Narrowing Differences' on Autos </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406145094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1446 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406145094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
may hold subcabinet-level talks next week to find ways to 
improve American access to Japan's auto and auto parts markets, 
a senior Trade Ministry official said Tuesday [14 June]. 
  The two parties are narrowing differences as much as 
possible 
during the current ongoing working-level auto trade talks, said 
the official at the Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
(MITI), who declined to be named. 
  But difficult issues will be left to the next stage of talks 
which may be held next week at the earliest between Sozaburo 
Okamatsu, MITI vice chief for international affairs, and Jeffrey 
Garten, U.S. commerce undersecretary for international trade, 
the official said, indicating that the controversial issue of 
how to set "objective criteria" in gauging openness of Japan's 
auto markets will be suspended. 
  Japan and the U.S. held working-level talks in Tokyo on 
Monday and Tuesday and will continue into an unscheduled third 
day Wednesday. 
  The senior MITI official said the two countries next week 
will resume talks designed to expand foreign access to Japan's 
glass market, a topic newly added to the priority fields of the 
trade "framework" negotiations. 

</TEXT>

