<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Mutual Understanding' Deepened </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Mutual Understanding' Deepened </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506105794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1047 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
ended three days of working-level auto trade talks in Tokyo 
Wednesday [15 June] apparently without reaching consensus on 
setting "objective criteria" as an instrument to gauge openness 
of Japan's auto market. 
  "Mutual understanding on differences has been deepened," an 
official at the Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
(MITI) told a press conference, adding the atmosphere at the 
talks was "cordial." 
  The officials of the two countries met Monday and Tuesday 
and 
then extended their talks for a third day Wednesday, to discuss 
measures to improve the U.S. access to the Japanese auto market 
and criteria to evaluate implementation of the measures, the 
MITI official said. 
  "The Japanese side fully understands the U.S. position, 
including a proposal on the most critical issue," the official 
said. 
  But the official declined to disclose further details of the 
talks, saying both parties agreed to keep quiet. 
  He said issues that have yet to be settled during the latest 
talks will be put on hold until the next round of working-level 
talks, expected to be held in Washington in the second half of 
next week. 
  The latest working-level gathering followed last week's 
subcabinet-level meeting in Tokyo where both parties failed to 
bridge difference over objective criteria, the thorniest issue 
under the bilateral trade "Framework" talks. 

</TEXT>

