<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kakizawa on Permanent UNSC Seat With Veto </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakizawa on Permanent UNSC Seat With Veto </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506111994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1049 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- Foreign minister Koji 
Kakizawa reiterated hope Wednesday [15 June] that Japan will 
become a permanent member with veto power on the UN Security 
Council. 
  "When a question arises and Japan cannot accept it at any 
cost, in order to reject it with all its might, it should be no 
problem for Japan to be a permanent member with veto," Kakizawa 
said in answer to questions at a House of Councillors Budget 
Committee session. 
  The minister said Japan should act to reflect views of the 
Asian region and small countries if it wins permanent membership 
with veto power. 
  Japan and Germany are now the only likely candidates for 
permanent seats should the Security Council expand the number 
from the current five, he said. 
  The council now groups Britain, China, France, Russia and 
the 
United States, which have veto power as the major victor nations 
of World War II, and 10 nonpermanent members selected from UN 
member nations for two-year terms. 
  Other countries including Brazil, Egypt, India and Nigeria 
have been named as candidates, but they have failed to win 
majority support among UN members, the minister said. 
  Earlier this month, Hisashi Owada, Japanese ambassador to 
the 
UN, asked a UN panel to discuss reorganization of the Security 
Council given Japan's bid for a permanent seat, but he did not 
mention veto. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

