<H3> <TI>   Keidanren Mission Arrives in Burma for Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Keidanren Mission Arrives in Burma for Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506111194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1057 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506111194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yangon [Rangoon], June 15 KYODO -- A large Japanese 
economic delegation arrived in Yangon Wednesday [15 June] for 
talks with Myanmarese [Burmese] leaders on promotion of 
bilateral trade and Japanese investment. 
  The 50-member delegation led by Kazuo Haruna, chairman of 
Marubeni Corp., represents the powerful Federation of Economic 
Organizations (Keidanren). Haruna is vice chairman of the 
federation. 
  During a four-day visit, the mission will confer with Prime 
Minister Gen. Than Shwe and other government and business 
leaders on ways for Japan to help promote the country's 
transition to a market economy, mission members said. 
  The mission members will also discuss Japan's investment in 
Myanmar and expansion of bilateral trade, they said. 
  It is the first visit to Myanmar by a large-scale Japanese 
economic delegation since the 1988 military coup and suppression 
of a democratic movement. 
  The mission includes senior officials of major Japanese 
corporations, including general trading firms, banks, department 
stores and heavy machinery makers. 
  The delegation was welcomed upon arrival by Myanmar 
officials 
led by Brig. Gen. David Abel, minister for national planning and 
economic development. 

</TEXT>

