<F P=102>   OW1406032994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0255 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406032994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- Japan's chief economic 
planner said Tuesday [14 Jun] he is not convinced the country's 
economy is rebounding. 
  Yoshio Terasawa, director general of the Economic Planning 
Agency (EPA), distanced himself from bank of Japan Governor 
Yasushi Mieno, who said Monday the economy has moved "one step 
toward a recovery." 
  "I cannot confidently say the economy has entered a recovery 
phase, although I do feel much better about it," Terasawa said 
at a press conference after a morning cabinet meeting. 
  He said he will wait before declaring an economic recovery, 
citing capital spending and foreign exchange rates as his main 
concerns. 
  "My concerns will dissapear if capital spending firms up," 
Teresawa said. 

