<DOCNO> FBIS4-29057 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas115_a_94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-115 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Increase in Investment in Public Sector Urged </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Increase in Investment in Public Sector Urged </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406100794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0946 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- The government should 
increase its investment in public-sector construction projects 
by an average 7.1 percent every year through fiscal 2000 to 
maintain an annual economic growth rate of 2 to 3.5 percent 
until 2010, a government study group said Tuesday [14 June]. 
  The group, formed by the Construction Ministry to estimate 
mid- and long-term construction investment by the public sector, 
said that spending by the private sector on building plants, 
offices and shops will remain weak until at least fiscal 2000. 
  Private-sector firms are taking time to adjust inventories 
accumulated during the "bubble economy" era of the late 1980's, 
it said, adding public-sector investment will be a key factor to 
sustain Japan's economic growth. It said the 7.1 percent 
desired increase is calculated based on an assumption that Japan 
wants to maintain an annual 3 to 3.5 percent economic growth in 
real terms through the 2000 business year, which ends March 2001. 
  Should Japan want to maintain the economic growth for 10 
years from the 2001 business year at a pace between 2.6 and 2.9 
percent, the government will find it necessary to increase its 
construction investment by an average 2.7 percent every year, 
the group added. The rate can be lower than for earlier years 
because private-sector investment will have recovered by then, 
it said. If the government increased such investment at lower 
paces, the economic growth target will not be sustainable, the 
group added. 
  With public-sector spending on construction projects boosted 
to the recommended rates in those periods, the scale of Japan's 
construction market, including housing, private-sector business 
facilities and public-sector construction projects, will reach 
about 870 trillion yen for the decade through the 2000 business 
year. The scale will then reach to about 1,180 trillion yen for 
the next decade, it said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

