<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-115 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tougher Measures Considered Against DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tougher Measures Considered Against DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506014694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0123 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1506014694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 (YONHAP) -- In the wake of North 
Korea's abrupt decision to quit the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA), hawkish voices are growing louder in the Japanese 
Government calling for the United Nations Security Council 
[UNSC] to adopt a resolution on immediate, rather than gradual, 
economic sanctions against North Korea, a senior Foreign 
Ministry official said Wednesday. 
  The official said, "Japan had demanded that the UNSC adopt a 
warning resolution first before monitoring the situation and 
passing a sanctions resolution against North Korea. But now 
that North Korea has withdrawn from the IAEA, Japan does not 
have any ground for proposing milder and gradual steps by the 
international community." 
  At a recent meeting with South Korea and the United States, 
Japan had proposed that the Security Council adopt a warning 
resolution first before taking the second step of imposing 
relatively mild economic sanctions. Under this proposal, if 
North Korea did not accept IAEA inspections despite the U.N. 
measures, the council would take strong action including 
suspension of trade and remittances from Koreans residing in 
Japan. 
  But with the Stalinist state's withdrawal from the IAEA, the 
Security Council may adopt a strong sanctions resolution from 
the outset that includes suspension of remittances by 
pro-Pyongyang Koreans in Japan to North Korea, the official said. 
  Meanwhile, the Japanese Government may send Foreign Minister 
Koji Kakizawa to the United States late this month to discuss 
future measures after a U.N. resolution is adopted, as the 
tension on the Korean peninsula continues to rise. 
  Japanese Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata talked with U.S. 
President Bill Clinton over the telephone Tuesday, promising 
that Japan will cooperate with the Security Council within the 
limits of its Constitution if sanctions are slapped on North 
Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

