<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: Arms Seized From SRV Fishermen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official: Arms Seized From SRV Fishermen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1506032594 Kuala Lumpur UTUSAN MALAYSIA in Malay 19 May 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BK1506032594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur UTUSAN MALAYSIA </F>
<F P=105>  Malay </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Johor Baharu, 18 May -- Illegal fishing 
activities in Malaysian waters by Vietnamese fishermen who are 
former military personnel well trained in warfare are posing a 
new threat to the country. This follows the discovery of a 
rocket-launcher and several automatic rifles in two Vietnamese 
fishing trawlers detained in Terengganu recently. 
  Abdul Hamid Syukor, chairman of the Marine Division of the 
Fishery Department said that from the national security 
viewpoint, the discovery of the weapons is serious and at the 
same time a danger to the country's maritime officials. "Even 
though there were no clashes when the weapons were seized, the 
seizure was something serious because these Vietnamese were well 
trained in using war weapons," he said to reporters after 
visiting the marine fishery center here. Therefore, maritime 
officers have been instructed to conduct thorough examinations 
on Vietnamese trawlers involved in illegal fishing in the area. 
  Abdul Hamid said the trawlers were found during the 
incidents 
on 4 and 7 March to be armed with one rocket-launcher, one light 
machine gun, two M-16 rifles, and two AK-47 rifles, as well as 
eight ammunition magazines, 13 rounds of 40mm ammunition, and 
485 rounds of ammunition. He added the two trawlers had been 
detained by two Royal Malaysian Navy patrol boats at 150 
nautical miles in Pahang waters early in the morning. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

