<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Keep Japan-U.S. Chip Accord in Effect </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo To Keep Japan-U.S. Chip Accord in Effect </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406121894 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 14 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1406121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Commenting on the Japan-U.S. Semiconductor 
Agreement that is due to be reviewed at the end of July, a 
senior official in the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry [MITI] said on 13 June, "The Japanese Government will 
not seek to repeal the agreement." His comment made clear that 
the Japanese Government plans to keep the agreement in effect 
without review until the end of July 1996. Japan and the United 
States are set to hold regular talks on the agreement for two 
days beginning 15 June in Tokyo. 
  The agreement, which was concluded between Japan and the 
United States in August 1991, is effective for five years. The 
agreement carries a provision that requires the two countries to 
"review whether to repeal it or not" at the end of July 1994. 
The agreement sets a 20 percent share of foreign-made 
semiconductors in the Japanese chip market as the target of 
effort. Japan has deeply repented concluding the agreement with 
the United States, claiming that the target of effort has been 
exploited by the United States as a numerical target. 
  For that reason, Japan has long thought of insisting on an 
early repeal of the agreement, but there is a strong view within 
MITI that, with the stalled Japan-U.S. economic framework talks 
just resumed, "Japan cannot argue with the United States over 
another sticky trade issue." 
  Though the Japanese Government has decided to keep the 
agreement in effect, the same senior MITI official made it clear 
that the Japanese Government will seek to repeal the agreement 
at the end of July 1996 when it expires, saying, "The agreement 
will not be extended after the end of July 1996." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

