<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Reviews Stance Toward DPRK in UNSC </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Reviews Stance Toward DPRK in UNSC </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506112794 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1506112794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In response to the DPRK (North Korea) announcement 
on its immediate withdrawal from the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA), a government source said on 14 June that the 
government had begun to review its stance toward UN Security 
Council [UNSC] resolutions. The Japanese Government has been 
taking a moderate attitude toward North Korea, calling for a 
UNSC warning before imposing any sanctions. However, some 
quarters in the government are calling for stronger actions to 
cope with North Korea's high-handed attitude. The government 
has reportedly started consulting the United States and the ROK 
to jointly urge the UNSC to adopt immediate sanctions. 
  On the same day, a top Foreign Ministry official hinted at a 
change in Japan's stance toward UNSC resolutions, saying: 
"Japan has been calling for step-by-step sanctions beginning 
with a warning by the UNSC, but this does not mean Japan wants 
to disturb the efforts of the international community." In 
addition, a Foreign Ministry source said stronger sanctions are 
likely to be imposed: "The UNSC may include Japan's ban on 
remittances to North Korea from the first stage." In that case, 
the government will face a difficult situation since the 
remittance ban is expected to arouse much controversy in Japan. 
  To cope with the North Korean nuclear issue, Japan, the 
United States, and the ROK held working-level talks in 
Washington on 4 June. Moreover, U.S. Under Secretary of State 
for Political Affairs Peter Tarnoff visited Japan and the ROK 
from 10 to 11 June to finalize a motion to be submitted to the 
UNSC. 
  The Japanese Government has been insisting that UNSC 
sanctions be implemented moderately on a step-by-step basis, 
since impatient measures would obtain support from neither China 
nor the Japanese public. In line with the moderate policy, 
Japan requested the UNSC issue a warning against North Korea 
prior to imposing sanctions. 
  The United States and the ROK initially showed consideration 
for Japan's position, and agreed to jointly seek step-by-step 
sanctions. Yet the two nations then showed slightly different 
positions, calling for a UNSC decision on suspension of 
technological aid and cultural exchanges by the United Nations, 
rather than bans on remittances or oil exports. 
  Following North Korea's announcement of its immediate 
withdrawal from the IAEA, the United States and the ROK have 
assumed a firm attitude. In a phone call with Foreign Minister 
Koji Kakizawa on the morning of 14 June, U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher hinted at a U.S. policy to strengthen the 
UNSC resolution, saying: "We may have to reconsider our proposal 
to the UNSC." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

