<H3> <TI>   TMD Use Urged To Counter DPRK Missiles </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    TMD Use Urged To Counter DPRK Missiles </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506122094 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1506122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the upper house Budget Committee session on 14 
June, Defense Agency Director General Atsushi Kanda expressed a 
positive stance toward introduction of the Theater Missile 
Defense (TMD) System. 
  In response to questions by Councillors Taizo Nozawa and 
Fumio Saito on Japan's defense system to counter threats from 
the DPRK's (North Korea) "Nodong-1" missiles, Kanda said: "We 
do not presently have an adequate defense system. We must have 
some sort of large-scale air defense system, such as the TMD." 
  The United States is planning to develop the TMD with the 
participation of Japan and other nations; and, at the Japan-U.S. 
security talks in March, foreign and defense ministers of the 
two nations agreed to "continue talks" on whether Japan should 
join the project. However, the Japanese Government has not so 
far determined its official policy on the project. 

</TEXT>

