<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Okinawa Vice Governor Vows To Halt Live Firing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Okinawa Vice Governor Vows To Halt Live Firing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506001894 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 14 Jun Evening 
Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1506001894 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kin -- Yoshimoto Masanori, lieutenant governor of 
the Okinawa Prefectural Government, observed a live-firing 
exercise conducted by the U.S. Marine Corps on Okinawa across 
Prefectural Highway No. 104 on the morning of 14 June. The 
live-firing exercise was the fifth such exercise since the 
beginning of this year. During his observation, the lieutenant 
governor surveyed how the highway was blockaded during the 
live-firing exercise and how the exercise affected the lives of 
residents. This is the first time that the lieutenant governor 
has observed an exercise since taking office. Meanwhile, a rally 
was staged to protest the live-firing exercise in Kodai, Igei 
District, under the auspices of the Okinawa Peace Movement 
Center. Rally participants blocked about 70 armed U.S. Marines 
trying to march through the rally, sparking a brief jostle 
between the Marines and labor unionists. 
  Lieutenant Governor Masanori and other prefectural 
government 
officials arrived at Prefectural Highway 14 at 0800 on the 
morning of 14 June when the live-fire exercise began. Katsuhiro 
Yoshida, chief of Kin town, told the lieutenant governor: 
"Forty years of live-firing exercise have turned Mt. Onna into 
a treeless mountain. Nature there is being destroyed. Red soil 
from training grounds where trees and rocks have disappeared are 
destroying Kin Bay. I want the live-firing exercise halted 
immediately." The town chief also pleaded with the lieutenant 
governor for an early enactment of the Military Land Conversion 
Law to promote the effective use of military lands to be 
returned. 
  In response, the lieutenant governor said: "U.S. Forces in 
Okinawa are certainly moving to cut back their training. 
However, the live-firing exercise is not a problem that can be 
resolved simply by streamlining and scaling back U.S. military 
bases in Okinawa. The exercises should be halted completely. I 
intend to speak out against the exercises with the residents' 
sufferings in mind." 
  One shell after another was fired into Mt. Onna when the 
lieutenant governor observed the live-firing exercise. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

