<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Not `Officially Informed' by DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Not `Officially Informed' by DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406092894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0838 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Leipzig (DDP/ADN) -- The International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) has not yet been officially informed that North 
Korea is to leave. Statements from the North Korean Foreign 
Ministry have only come through the media, IAEA spokesman 
Hans-Friedrich Meyer said today on Mitteldeutscher Rundfunk 
(MDR). The IAEA inspectors have also not yet been asked to 
leave the country. 
  Meyer stressed that North Korea leaving the IAEA does not 
automatically mean it has to leave the Nuclear Nonproliferation 
Treaty. Separate control agreements exist here. These also 
still allow for on-the-spot checks. 
  According to the IAEA spokesman, the nuclear danger posed by 
North Korea is being "played up by the media." "The IAEA has 
never said that North Korea has bombs." 

</TEXT>

