<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA `Expecting' Confirmation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA `Expecting' Confirmation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506093194 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0926 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt am Main (DDP/ADN) -- The International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) is expecting written confirmation 
today of North Korea's withdrawal from the organization, IAEA 
spokesman David Kyd said on Hessischer Rundfunk radio today. At 
the same time, Kyd contradicted reports over the past few days 
that North Korea had threatened to withdraw from the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty. "North Korea has not done that," Kyd 
stressed. 
  North Korea has been in a grey area after it announced in 
1993 that it would leave the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty but 
then withdrew this application at the last minute. "They are 
neither a member nor a nonmember of the treaty, but the 
community of nations considers North Korea still to be a 
member." Now we are concerned only with how the country will 
react in the future, he said. 
  As things stand, it does not appear that North Korea wants 
to 
sell material suitable for the production of nuclear weapons, 
Kyd said, but they had to continue to follow developments. 
Despite reports from the secret services, it is still not clear 
whether North Korea has nuclear bombs. The only thing they are 
certain of is that the country has more plutonium in its 
possession than it officially admitted to, Kyd said. 

</TEXT>

