<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Minister: No IAEA Nuclear Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Minister: No IAEA Nuclear Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506053094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0451 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506053094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- North Korea's Minister of 
People's Armed Forces O Chin-u said North Korea will never again 
permit inspections of its nuclear facilities by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), in a speech carried 
Wednesday by Radio Pyongyang. 
  In a broadcast monitored in Tokyo by the SHIN-A NEWS AGENCY, 
O said North Korea took the "defensive measure of pulling out of 
the IAEA and will never again permit inspections" because of the 
agency's "arrogant and insolent" demands for nuclear checks. 
  The broadcast comes as IAEA officials are pointing out that 
despite North Korea's announcement Monday that it was pulling 
out of the agency, it is still subject to nuclear inspections by 
the IAEA under the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty. 
  O's speech was made at a welcome reception for a Vietnamese 
military delegation visiting Pyongyang, led by Defense Minister 
Gen. Doan Khue, SHIN-A reported. 

</TEXT>

