<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   APEC Conference on Manpower Development Opens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    APEC Conference on Manpower Development Opens </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1306010594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0017 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1306010594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 13 (YONHAP) -- The Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation (APEC) forum opened a four-day working-level meeting 
here Monday to discuss manpower development. 
  The 10th meeting is being attended by representatives from 
17 
APEC member countries, Chile, which is scheduled to join the 
group in November, and the Pacific Economic Cooperation 
Committee (PECC). 
  Discussions will be held in four subcommittees -- the 
education forum, the economic development network, the 
management network and the industrial technology network. 
  Participants are expected to concentrate on an occupational 
training program proposed by South Korea at the fifth APEC 
ministerial conference and the manpower development projects 
agreed at the APEC leaders' meeting in Seattle, Washington, last 
year. 
  The APEC occupational training program calls for exchanges 
of 
teachers, technology and technicians, job training, equipment 
support and the formation of a network to exchange information 
on occupational training. 
  Pae Yong-sik, an official of South Korea's Economic Planning 
Board and chairman of the conference, said the meeting is aimed 
at promoting the introduction to developing countries of 
management skills from advanced nations. 
  South Korea hopes to foster a favorable investment and trade 
climate in other countries by providing occupational training 
for workers from developing states, Pae said. 

</TEXT>

