<F P=100> Mongolia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Democratic Rebirth Party Holds First Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Democratic Rebirth Party Holds First Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606135894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0749 
gmt 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Kim Boldokhonov] </F>
  [Text] Ulaanbaatar, 6 Jun -- The aim of the newly created 
Mongolian Democratic Rebirth Party is the renewal of the country 
on the basis of democratic principles and taking into account 
the specific conditions and tasks of our society at the present 
stage, as well as the principles of human civilization as a 
whole. Dashiyn Byambasuren said this today in an interview with 
an ITAR-TASS correspondent. He opened the founding forum of 
this new political force today with brief introductory remarks. 
The former head of the first multiparty coalition government in 
Mongolia's history set up an organizing committee with a group 
of like-minded people, which submitted a report "On the 
sociopolitical situation in the country and the tasks of the 
party" and the draft rules and program of the Mongolian 
Democratic Rebirth Party for debate by delegates. 
  We favor a state with strong democratic power, a society of 
civic accord and genuine market relations in the economy. Our 
party regards strong presidential power and a small, highly 
professional parliament to be most acceptable for Mongolian 
conditions, D. Byambasuren noted. 
  On the matter of collaboration with other political forces, 
D. Byambasuren said: "We favor close cooperation with all 
parties if our views are common or similar. The Mongolian 
Democratic Rebirth Party favors the formation of a general 
democratic front." 
  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian at 1117 GMT on 6 
June notes the following: 
  "Congress delegates adopted the party's rules and program 
and 
elected its ruling bodies. Dashiyn Byambasuren becomes chairman 
of the party, and the publicist Luvsangiyn Purevdorj its general 
secretary. With this the congress concluded its work." 

</TEXT>

