<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Assembly Proceedings Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Assembly Proceedings Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Communique No. 15 Issued </H4>

<F P=102> BK1506155294 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1430 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1506155294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The National Assembly Office issues Communique No. 
15 as follows: 
  On 15 June the National Assembly worked at the conference 
hall under the direction of National Assembly Chairman Nong Duc 
Manh. At the beginning of the working day, all deputies stood in 
a minute to commemorate Comrade Nguyen Van Cu, National Assembly 
deputy from Hanoi City, who passed away on 13 June. Then the 
National Assembly deputies put questions to some members of the 
government cabinet. 
  1. Tran Dinh Hoan, minister of labor, war invalids, and 
social welfare, answered questions on changes to policies 
regarding wounded combatants, families of war dead, and other 
people with meritorious deeds; one-off severance pay for cadres 
and employees leaving their positions; adjustment of pension for 
cadres and employees in accordance with the new wage policy; the 
situation of spontaneous immigration and measures to resolve the 
issue; and the situation and measures to deal with drug 
addiction. 
  2. Construction Minister Ngo Xuan Loc answered questions on 
issues related to the house price appraisal policy. 
  3. Trade Minister Le Van Triet answered questions on the 
cases of numerous motorcycles imported without permits by some 
business establishments through Saigon and Haiphong Ports; 
imported paper and its impact on the local paper industry; and 
the detainment of 38 motorcars imported by some business 
establishments at the Binh Dinh Market Control Force Office. 
  4. Dau Ngoc Xuan, minister chairman of the State Commission 
of Cooperation and Investment, answered questions on the 
elimination of irritating procedures in licensing foreign 
investment projects in Vietnam; and the situation and prospects 
regarding foreign invested projects. 
  5. Phan Ngoc Tuong, minister chairman of State Commission of 
Organization and Personnel, answered questions on changes to the 
Decree No. 46 on the policy on grassroots cadres at ward and 
village levels; the cases of cars imported temporarily then 
exported again in Dong Nai, Song Be, and Tay Ninh; the situation 
and results of the fight against corruption and smuggling; and 
government directions regarding this fight. 
  6. Tran Hoan, minister of culture and information, answered 
questions on issues related to state management to cultural 
activities. 
  After Ministers Tran Dinh Hoan, Le Van Triet, Dau Ngoc Xuan, 
Phan Ngoc Tuong, and Tran Hoan finished their answers, 17 
deputies raised other issues that needed further explanation. 
They are: Tran Thi Bach Tuyet from Dong Nai; Tran Quoc Thai 
from Ha Tinh; Dam Van Nguy from Cao Bang; Vu thi Ngoc Dau from 
Thai Binh; Le Quoc Khanh, Nguyen Don, Nguyen Ba Khanh from Quang 
Nam-Danang; Cu Hoa Van from Lao Cai; Trieu Thi Nhay from Yen 
Bai; Tran Thi Le Thu, Vo Van Luoc from Binh Dinh; Nguyen Trong 
Khanh from Vinh Phu; Dang Thi Thanh Huong from Quang Ninh; Tran 
Van Cua from Minh Hai; Nguyen Quoc Thuoc from Nghe An; Le Van 
Tri from Thanh Hoa [name as heard]; and Nguyen van Rang from 
Minh Hai [name as heard]. 
  The aforementioned ministers continued to answer the 
newly-raised questions. On 16 June the National Assembly will 
hold a plenary session at the conference hall. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

