<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Reportage on Reaction to DPRK Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reportage on Reaction to DPRK Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    DPRK Action Based on `Plan' </H4>

<F P=102> OW1406120294 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 14 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1406120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Akio Takahata] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 13 Jun -- Concerning the DPRK's 
announcement on 13 June of its withdrawal from the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), a UN diplomatic source indicated: 
"The act is in line with a carefully-worked out plan for phased 
steps to deal with moves of the United States and Europe." The 
DPRK's withdrawal from the IAEA will not immediately lead to its 
official secession from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty 
(NPT). Pyongyang's decision to pull out of the IAEA is 
considered an act aimed at upgrading its diplomatic cards by 
showing the United States and the United Nations its readiness 
"to withdraw from the NPT anytime." 
  The purpose of participating in the IAEA is to promote 
exchanges, and to study knowhow and technology for the peaceful 
use of nuclear power -- which is a different purpose from 
joining the NPT. Also, according to the rules, the DPRK's 
withdrawal from the IAEA will not immediately lead to its 
departure from the NPT. 
  In a government statement, North Korea referred to its 
"special position" of holding up a decision to withdraw from the 
NPT. It is necessary for Pyongyang to maintain this special 
position to continue to reject demands to accept nuclear 
inspections in accordance with safeguard arrangements, while 
remaining in the NPT. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

