<H3> <TI>   Continued Reportage on Reaction to DPRK Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reportage on Reaction to DPRK Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    DPRK `Tough' Nuclear Position Viewed </H4>

<F P=102> OW1606090794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 16 June 
Morning Edition p 8 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1606090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Summary" of interview with Yi Tong-pok, former special </F>
assistant to the ROK prime minister, by NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN's 
Yukiyoshi Fujimura in Seoul; date not given; first paragraph is 
NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN introduction] 
  [Text] The ROK has so far taken a generally calm attitude 
with regard to the issue of the DPRK's (North Korea) suspected 
development of nuclear arms. However, after North Korea started 
to adopt a tough position, beginning with the replacement of 
nuclear fuel rods, quarters concerned and experts in South Korea 
are beginning to take a more pessimistic view that "may be the 
suspicions are true." One such person is Yi Tong-pok, former 
special assistant to the prime minister, and spokesman for the 
ROK delegation during the North-South prime ministerial talks. 
We interviewed Yi on what the DPRK will do next. 
  [Fujimura] How do you view the tough attitude adopted by 
North Korea? 
  [Yi] Looking at the recent exchanges, I do not think they 
are merely using the development of nuclear arms as a "nuclear 
card." They have now clearly indicated their intention to 
develop nuclear arms. 
  [Fujimura] What do you think is the present state of their 
development of nuclear weapons? 
  [Yi] North Korea already possesses enough plutonium to make 
one to three atomic bombs. Given another two years, they will 
actually be able to make nuclear bombs. They are also building 
two new reactors. Compared to existing reactors, one will have 
10 times the capacity of current reactors, and the other, 40 
times. Together, they can produce 200 kg of plutonium each year. 
This means that if things go on like this, North Korea will 
become a nuclear superpower in three or four years. 
  [Fujimura] Will North Korea compromise under the pressure of 
economic sanctions? 
  [Yi] Because the United States has been sending the wrong 
signals to North Korea recently, North Korea is taking the 
United States lightly. It probably thinks that the United 
States is incapable of imposing economic sanctions. 
  [Fujimura] Do you think there is a possibility that North 
Korea will start a war? 
  [Yi] I cannot really say the possibility does not exist, but 
I think the possibility is very slim. North Korea has merely 
conducted test launches of its missiles; they are not yet ready 
for active deployment. With their present military capability, 
they are quite incapable of launching an attack. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

