<H4>    Financial Transactions Not Suspended </H4>

<F P=102> OW1606054894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 16 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1606054894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 16 Jun Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] One of the sanctions against the DPRK (North Korea) 
for its suspected nuclear arms development is to suspend 
remittance. Concerning this measure, a government source stated 
on the evening of 15 June: "According to the Finance Ministry, 
it will be difficult to take this measures without a UN 
resolution. In saying it is difficult, the ministry means such 
a measure cannot be taken." 
  It is speculated that in the Foreign Exchange and Foreign 
Trade Control Law that restrictions can be imposed on payment 
"for the purpose of faithfully fulfilling international treaties 
that our country has concluded or other international 
commitments." According to the same source, the judgment seems 
to indicate that a UN resolution can be taken as an 
"international commitment" but this regulation cannot be applied 
to "multilateral-type" sanctions. 

</TEXT>

