<DOCNO> FBIS4-29176 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas116__a94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-116-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Reportage on Reaction to DPRK Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reportage on Reaction to DPRK Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Impact on Industry Analyzed </H4>

<F P=102> OW1606013394 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 9 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1606013394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article] </F>
  [Text] With the DPRK (North Korea) having announced its 
withdrawal from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), 
the question of imposing sanctions against that country has 
entered a critical stage. However, the sanctions are not 
expected to affect Japanese industry much because the scale of 
Japan's trade with North Korea is small while travel between 
these two nations is close to nonexistent. 
<H5>  Trade </H5>
  Japan-DPRK trade ran to about 100 billion yen a year from 
the 
late seventies and early eighties. During that period, Japan's 
exports to North Korea continuously exceeded its imports by a 
ratio of almost 2:1. But since North Korea announced a policy 
to balance imports and exports in 1986, Japan's exports to the 
country decreased by half [the next year] and Japan has imported 
more than it has exported since 1987. Overall trade came down 
to a 50-60 billion yen level. 
  Japan's main exports to North Korea used to be manufactured 
products, like machinery. But since 1992, textile products, 
such as woolen fabrics, and automobiles have been its major 
export items. As for imports from North Korea, nonferrous metals 
used to be major products, but recently men's suits and coats, 
mushrooms, and anthracite coal have come to be major items. 
<H5>  Aviation and Traveling </H5>
  There are no regular airline services between Japan and 
North 
Korea. Only chartered planes operate from Nagoya and Niigata 
Airports. Mushrooms are the major air-freighted product from 
North Korea, and personnel exchanges are limited to special 
delegations. In case sanctions are taken, all of these airline 
operations will be suspended. 
  As for surface shipping, even the Transport Ministry does 
not 
know accurate conditions. However, it is estimated that about 
100 North Korean ships enter Japan every year. With 
instructions from the Foreign Affairs Ministry or the Defence 
Agency, the Maritime Safety Agency can conduct on-the-spot 
inspections on these ships entering Japan by sending patrol 
boats, but it is still uncertain how far the agency can go in 
restricting entry of North Korean ships as part of economic 
sanctions. 
<H5>  Reaction From Business Circles </H5>
  Shoichiro Toyoda, chairman of the Japan Federation of 
Economic Organizations [Keidanren], at a 13 June news 
conference, commented: "This [DPRK issue] is an important 
security issue for Japan, and we must take it seriously. I hope 
that, if possible, North Korea will soon revert to a position 
that can be accepted by the international community so that 
sanctions will be avoided." Minoru Makihara, president of 
Mitsubishi Corporation, said: "I think Japan can make moves on 
its own more actively in close contact with the Untied States. 
Although the sanctions' impact on Japan's economy will be 
small, this is a problem that is taking place in Asia. How will 
the government deal with it if the United States decides to wash 
its hands of this matter?" 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29177 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas116__a94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-116-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Reportage on Reaction to DPRK Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reportage on Reaction to DPRK Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Effect on Politics Evaluated </H4>

<F P=102> OW1506134594 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Jun 
94 Morning Edition p 2-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1506134594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The North Korean nuclear issue, which has grown 
increasingly tense following North Korea's announcement of its 
withdrawal from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), 
has caused a subtle ripple in the confused political situation 
in Japan. Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of Shinseito [Japan 
Renewal Party]; Michio Watanabe, former deputy prime minister 
and foreign minister; and Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, former chairman of 
the Policy Research Council of the opposition Liberal Democratic 
Party [LDP], who are all proponents of a 
"conservative-conservative coalition," are pushing for a 
realignment of established political parties on the basis of a 
policy consensus. They are citing the North Korean nuclear 
issue as one important policy that needs a consensus. With the 
current Diet session set to close on 29 June, the North Korean 
nuclear issue may become not only an important diplomatic task 
for Japan, but one factor in unsettling the political situation. 
  As far as the North Korean nuclear issue is concerned, the 
government's position is: "There is no option for Japan but to 
sincerely carry out what the United Nations decides" (said a 
senior Foreign Ministry official). Some government officials 
are voicing concern over Japan's overreaction to North Korea's 
withdrawal from the IAEA, saying: "What is important is that 
our nation must refrain from making a big fuss. North Korea 
would be pleased to find its simple announcements or comments 
trigging a big fuss in Japan" (said a government source). 
  The North Korean nuclear crisis was a hot issue in the 
Hosokawa government, the handling of which the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ] bitterly disputed with Shinseito and 
Komeito. The SDPJ may become a hurdle for proponents of the 
"conservative- conservative coalition" who intend to seek a 
coalition by "putting aside past grudges." 
  While the United Nations is certain to begin a full-fledged 
debate on sanctions against North Korea, China is still taking a 
wary position. The prevailing view is that serious domestic 
debates will be held in "the far future" on how Japan should 
actually deal with sanctions (said a Foreign Ministry source). 
In the closing days of the current Diet session, the political 
situation is expected to be strained over a no-confidence motion 
against the Hata cabinet, and the handling of a bill on the 
demarcation for a new single-seat constituency system and a new 
proportional representation system; no drastic developments are 
expected to occur before the current Diet session closes. 
  North Korea has made it clear it wants to negotiate only 
with 
the United States. Japanese Government officials are concerned 
that the "North Korean nuclear issue could become a factor in 
destabilizing the political situation in Japan" because the 
issue is bound to strain things (said a senior Foreign Ministry 
official). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

