<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Ask China To Lower Tariffs on 300 Items </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo To Ask China To Lower Tariffs on 300 Items </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506084494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 15 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1506084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 15 Jun Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The government will submit an additional request as 
early as this week to China, which wants to become a GATT 
member this year, asking it to lower tariffs on about 300 mining 
and manufacturing industrial goods, including chemical and 
electric appliances. Japan has already asked China to lower 
tariffs and remove nontariff barriers on some 3,800 goods. The 
total number of goods, if the items on the additional request 
are included, will become about 4,100. 
  Regarding the 3,800 goods, the government submitted a demand 
last March and received a tentative answer from China in late 
May. However, since the contents of the response are not 
"satisfactory," (according to a government source), the 
government, in addition to submitting the additional request, 
plans to work on China during future bilateral negotiations to 
positively accept the demands. 
  Regarding China's GATT membership, a GATT working-level 
meeting is scheduled to be held in Geneva starting on 27 June. 
It seems that Japan and China will have bilateral negotiations 
at that time. 

</TEXT>

