<H3> <TI>   Seminar on U.S. Car Sales Held in Tokyo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seminar on U.S. Car Sales Held in Tokyo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406122394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1143 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406122394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- About 250 representatives 
of Japanese and foreign automakers and dealers attended a 
seminar held in Tokyo Tuesday [14 June] to help promote sales of 
cars imported from the United States. 
  The Japan Automobile Dealers Association, which sponsored 
the 
session, told those attending that the number of Japanese 
dealers selling imported cars has increased because they are not 
barred by affiliated makers from selling products of other 
manufacturers. The association said the number of such dealers 
will continue to increase if imported cars are competitive in 
quality and price. 
  Konen Suzuki, president of Ford Motor Co. (Japan) Ltd., and 
other representatives of the Big Three U.S. automakers explained 
their marketing strategies in Japan. 
  The seminar was organized by the association to help promote 
Japan-U.S. negotiations for a new framework of bilateral trade. 
The association said it plans to hold a similar seminar for 
cars imported from Europe. 

</TEXT>

