<H3> <TI>   Okinawa Urges U.S. To Cut Bases in POST Ad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Okinawa Urges U.S. To Cut Bases in POST Ad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606075394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0733 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606075394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 16 KYODO -- Okinawa Prefecture 
urged the United States to curtail its bases in southernmost 
Japan in a full-page WASHINGTON POST advertisement Thursday [16 
June], saying aircraft noise and shooting drills are hurting the 
residents' living conditions and the environment. 
  The ad is timed with Okinawa Governor Masahide Ota's visit 
to 
the U.S., starting Thursday, to press the White House and the 
Pentagon on the issue. Ota said in the ad that his past two 
visits to the U.S. to seek a solution to the problems failed to 
produce any concrete results. 
  Ota is scheduled to meet commanding officers of the 
Hawaii-based U.S. Pacific Fleet. In Washington he will hold 
talks with State Department and Pentagon officials as well as 
with members of the Senate and House of Representatives Armed 
Services Committees. 
  Some 75 percent of U.S. military facilities in Japan are 
concentrated in Okinawa, comprising a cluster of islands 
northeast of Taiwan. The ad calls for the return of the U.S. 
naval port in Naha, and the abolition of parachute training and 
live-ammunition exercises. 
  Okinawa was reunited with Japan on May 15, 1972 after a 
27-year occupation, under the condition that U.S. Forces would 
be allowed to continue to use the bases there. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

