<H3> <TI>   Further Reports Concerning DPRK Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reports Concerning DPRK Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    PRC's Position Unchanged </H4>

<F P=102> OW1606064594 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 0300 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1606064594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report; from "NHK News" program] </F>
  [Text] Li Daoyu, Chinese ambassador to the United Nations, 
in a 15 June interview with NHK, declined to directly comment on 
the draft sanctions resolution that the United States has 
prepared to submit to the UN Security Council [UNSC], merely 
saying: China's position remains unchanged. The PRC has 
maintained a cautious stance on imposing sanctions against the 
DPRK. 
  As a result, it is expected that for the time being, 
behind-the-scenes maneuverings -- including possible revisions 
to the draft resolution -- will continue among UNSC member 
nations, with attention focused on how China will react to the 
U.S. proposal. 

</TEXT>

