<H3> <TI>   Further Reports Concerning DPRK Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reports Concerning DPRK Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    SDPJ Pushes U.S.-DPRK Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW1606083394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0809 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606083394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 16 KYODO -- The Social Democratic Party 
(SDP) [SDPJ -- Social Democratic Party of Japan] will urge 
Japan, the United States and China to make efforts to reopen 
high-level talks between Washington and Pyongyang on North 
Korea's suspected nuclear arms development, a party official 
said Thursday [16 June]. 
  Kazo Watanabe, director of the second largest opposition 
party's General Affairs Bureau, told a news conference at the 
Japan National Press Club that Japan and North Korea should also 
resume talks as early as possible to establish diplomatic 
relations. Officials of the (North) Korean Workers' Party have 
told SDP officials in Pyongyang they want to unconditionally 
restart normalization talks stalled since November 1992, 
Watanabe said. 
  An SDP delegation headed by Watanabe visited North Korea for 
six days up to Wednesday as part of efforts to promote ties with 
the North's ruling party. The SDP has traditionally maintained 
close relations with the Korean Workers' Party. 
  Watanabe also said the SDP will oppose the idea of slapping 
sanctions on North Korea as a means of ending Pyongyang's 
alleged quest for nuclear weapons. 
  Two legislators of the primary opposition Liberal Democratic 
Party are also visiting Pyongyang for talks on North Korea's 
nuclear program. 

</TEXT>

