<H3> <TI>   Vice Finance Minister on Trade Surplus With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice Finance Minister on Trade Surplus With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606091794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0910 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 16 KYODO -- Japan's trade surplus 
appears to be shrinking, but the still-rising gap with the 
United States is worrisome, Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito 
said Thursday. 
  The merchandise trade figures for May released earlier in 
the 
day underscored "the rising imports and falling exports in terms 
of volume," Saito told a regular news meeting. "But I want to 
see if that becomes a fixed trend, and I'm worried about the 
unchanged (upward) trend with the U.S.," Saito said. 
  The May preliminary figures showed that Japan's surplus fell 
15.9 percent from a year before to score the first fall in six 
months, but the gap with the U.S. continued to rise for the 
third month in a row, gaining 7.5 percent. 

</TEXT>

