<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Election System Supported by Majority of LH </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Election System Supported by Majority of LH </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406131894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1242 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- A majority of the 511 
members of the Lower House [LH] have supported an interparty 
campaign calling for the next general election to be held under 
the new election system combining single-seat constituencies and 
proportional representation, organizers of the drive said 
Tuesday [14 June]. 
  The organizers have collected signatures of 306 lower house 
legislators, including 42 ministers and parliamentary vice 
ministers who signed on condition that their names not be 
disclosed, they said. 
  The other 264 signers comprise 60 lawmakers from the Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP), 34 from the Social Democratic Party 
(SDP) [SDPJ-- Social Democratic Party of Japan], 49 from 
Shinseito, 42 from Komeito, 28 from the Japan New Party, 14 from 
the Democratic Socialist Party (DSP), 21 from New Party 
Sakigake, Group Seiun and Minshu No Kaze, five from the Liberal 
Party, five from the New Party Mirai, three from the former 
Kaikaku No Kai and three independents, they said. 
  The campaign was arranged to prevent the LDP and the SDP 
from 
proposing a no-confidence motion against Prime Minister Tsutomu 
Hata that could result in an early lower house general election 
held under the still-existing multiseat constituency system, 
they said. 
  The organizers will show Hata the results Wednesday and urge 
him not to dissolve the lower house, they said. They will also 
meet SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama and LDP President Yohei Kono 
to brief them on the outcome. 
  Yuji Tsushima, acting chairman of the LDP Policy Affairs 
Research Council, and other organizers representing other 
parties met reporters to release the results of the campaign. 
  The new electoral system, under which 300 out of a reduced 
500 lower house seats would be elected from single-seat 
constituencies and the remaining 200 through a proportional 
representation system, was enacted in January, but it cannot 
take effect until boundaries of the 300 new single-seat 
constituencies are formally legislated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

