<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition, Opposition Agree on Electoral Reform Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coalition, Opposition Agree on Electoral Reform Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406141594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1359 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- House of Councillors 
lawmakers from the ruling coalition and the opposition camp 
agreed Tuesday [14 June] on a wishy-washy plan for electoral 
reform in the upper house, skirting all drastic reform proposals. 
  Following a series of meetings by party representatives, it 
was agreed to increase the number of seats in four 
constituencies and cut those in four others to achieve more 
balanced representation. One seat will be added each to 
constituencies in Kanagawa, Saitama, Miyagi and Gifu 
Prefectures, while Hokkaido will lose two and Hyogo and Fukuoka 
one each. 
  The ruling and opposition parties excluding the Japan 
Communist Party plan to submit the reform bills in the current 
Diet session. Proposals to reduce the total number of seats by 
two from the current 252 and to introduce a vote-for-individual 
formula into the 100-seat proportional representation system 
were both scuttled. 
  Members of the 252-seat upper house are elected either in 
multiseat constituencies or in a 100-seat proportional 
representation system, in which votes are cast for parties, not 
individuals. 
  Because the parties failed to agree on any striking 
electoral 
reform, the upper house poll scheduled for summer will see 
little change from the current system. Diet passage of the 
proposed changes, however, is far from secured, with the end of 
the current session on June 29 approaching, political sources 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

