<H3> <TI>   Takemura Predicts No Extension for Diet Session </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Takemura Predicts No Extension for Diet Session </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506064894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0637 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506064894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- The current regular Diet 
session will wind up without an extension on June 29 and a new 
electoral map for the House of Representatives will be discussed 
in the next session, a key political leader predicted Wednesday 
[15 June]. 
  "I do not think there will be an extension of the Diet 
term," 
Masayoshi Takemura, the leader of New Party Sakigake [Shinto 
Sakigake], told a luncheon at the Japan National Press Club. 
  Although the government must have wanted to submit an 
as-yet-unformulated bill that redraws the electoral map for the 
lower house and to extend the 150-day Diet session, it runs 
short of time, he said. 
  "Therefore, there will be no need to extend the Diet term 
for 
debate on key issues," said Takemura, the chief cabinet 
secretary in the last government of Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa. 
  The 15-member Sakigake left the governing coalition in April 
due to differences over major policies and political approach 
with other coalition partners. 
  The administration of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, Japan's 
first minority government since 1955, once appeared ready to 
extend the current Diet session and act upon the redistricting 
legislation in a move to avoid a possible no-confidence motion 
from the opposition camp. 
  The main opposition Liberal Democratic Party has made it 
clear it plans to bring down the Hata government in a 
no-confidence vote. The Social Democratic Party, the 
second-largest opposition force, has also threatened to submit 
the motion by itself. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

