<H3> <TI>   Lower House Approves Product Liability Bill </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lower House Approves Product Liability Bill </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606103494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1006 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 16 KYODO -- The House of 
Representatives on Thursday [16 June] approved a bill to 
introduce product liability for the first time in Japan and sent 
it to the House of Councillors. 
  The upper house is expected to endorse the bill as early as 
next week, setting the stage for the enforcement of the 
legislation one year later. The new law, the first of its kind 
in Japan, will make it easier for consumers to prove 
manufacturer liability for damage stemming from defective 
products. 
  The legislation had met strong opposition from some 
lawmakers 
within the Liberal Democratic Party, the largest opposition 
party, who had demanded that blood products be exempted. The 
Japan Society of Blood Transfusion had joined the LDP in 
demanding an exemption of blood for transfusion, saying that the 
bill could hurt the blood supply. The opposition did not lead 
any change in the draft bill, but forced the government to 
attach seven resolutions making it clear that an unavoidable 
spread of viruses through blood transfusion at the current 
scientific standards and blood transfusion reactions do not 
constitute defects. 

</TEXT>

