<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports on U.S.-Japan Semiconoductor Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on U.S.-Japan Semiconoductor Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Microchip Pact Extension Issue </H4>

<F P=102> OW1606063594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0604 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606063594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 16 KYODO -- The latest Japan-U.S. 
semiconductor trade talks did not take up the issue of whether 
or not to terminate a bilateral microchip pact after the July 
1996 expiration, a senior Japanese Trade Ministry official said 
Thursday [16 June]. 
  "During the just-ended trade session, both parties agreed to 
take time toward July 31 this year in studying the issue," 
Hideaki Kumano, vice international trade and industry minister, 
told a press conference. 
  Japan and the United States must decide whether or not to 
end 
the 1991 chip accord by the end of July. 
  The accord calls for Japan to maintain a "gradual and 
steady" 
increase in the foreign share of the Japanese microchip market 
above 20 percent. 
  The two-day microchip trade talks followed an announcement 
that foreign-made semiconductors continued to seize more than 20 
percent of the Japanese market in the January-March period. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

