<H3> <TI>   Hearing on U.S. Apple Imports Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hearing on U.S. Apple Imports Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506054494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0434 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506054494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 15 KYODO -- The Ministry of 
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries said Wednesday [15 June] it 
will hold a public hearing in Tokyo on July 7 and 8 on imports 
of U.S.-grown apples. 
  The ministry said it will take applications from those who 
want to speak at the hearing until June 24. 
  With U.S. quarantine measures to prevent apple disease 
having 
already cleared Japanese requirements, Japan plans to lift its 
ban on imports of U.S. apples this fall. 
  Japan has kept its market closed to U.S. apples, citing 
worms 
and disease which it had said could contaminate Japanese crops. 
  Ministry sources said that at a similar hearing in April 
last 
year on imports of New Zealand apples, domestic apple growers 
clamored for the continued ban on foreign apples. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

