<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Withdrawal From NPT Depends on `Developments' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Withdrawal From NPT Depends on `Developments' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1606045894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0446 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1606045894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, June 16 (KCNA) -- As already reported, 
the Foreign Ministry of the Democratic People's Republic of 
Korea in a statement of its spokesman declared that the DPRK 
would immediately withdraw from the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA] in answer to the grave encroachment upon the 
dignity and sovereignty of the DPRK by the Secretariat of the 
agency. 
  In this regard, NODONG SINMUN today says the DPRK's 
withdrawal from the IAEA is a legitimate self-defensive measure 
to defend its sovereignty and existence as a dignified 
independent, sovereign state. 
  The responsibility for its withdrawal from the IAEA rests 
entirely with the agency, the analyst says, and goes on: 
  We joined the agency in September 1974, believing its 
impartiality and hoping that its assistance would be conducive 
to our peaceful nuclear activities. 
  After we signed the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty [NPT] 
in 
December 1985 and concluded the safeguards agreement in January 
1992, however, the Secretariat of the agency has zealously 
joined the United States in its moves to isolate and stifle the 
DPRK, contrary to its mission and function, and some officials 
of the Secretariat intentionally created "inconsistency" and 
adopted a resolution demanding "a special inspection" of our 
military sites which have nothing to do with nuclear activities. 
  Such unjustifiable acts of theirs resulted in forcing the 
DPRK to declare its withdrawal from the NPT. 
  It was for the removal of the U.S. nuclear threat and the 
denuclearization of the Korean peninsula that we joined the NPT. 
The Secretariat of the agency, however, encroached upon the 
supreme interests of our state and cried to stifle the DPRK, 
abusing the NPT. Under this condition, we could no longer hope 
for its help. Later, we temporarily suspended the effectuation 
of our declared withdrawal from the NPT in June 1993 on 
condition that the DPRK-U.S. talks for a peaceful solution to 
the nuclear issue would continue on an equal and fair basis. 
  Even in a unique status following the temporary suspension 
of 
our withdrawal from the NPT, we had honestly accepted 
inspections for the continuity of safeguards and allowed even 
"an additional inspection." But the United States and some 
pro-U.S. officials of the Secretariat had used inspections as a 
leverage for infringing on our sovereignty and stifling the 
DPRK, refusing to recognize its special status and intentionally 
laying obstacles to the DPRK-U.S. talks. 
  The agency's anti-DPRK moves reached the extent where it 
adopted an unreasonable "resolution" on the discontinuation of 
"its assistance" to the DPRK at the meeting of the governors' 
board on June 10, demanding the opening of our military sites to 
public under the pretext of the nuclear issue. 
  Such being the situation, we did not feel the need to have 
dealings with the agency any more and reached the conclusion 
that we could no longer hope for its help. 
  Now that we declared the withdrawal from the agency, we will 
not bound in the legal point of view to the "resolutions" or 
steps which the governors' board has adopted and taken or will 
adopt and take in the future, and we are not obliged to 
implement them. Now the agency is not in a position to dictate 
to us. 
  The freedom of choice is not a monopoly of the United States 
and the Secretariat of the agency. 
  Whether our special status following the temporary 
suspension 
of the withdrawal from the NPT is removed or we completely 
withdraw from it, fully depends on the future developments. 
  If the United States and its allies resort to a strong arm 
to 
stifle the DPRK, ignoring its special status and abusing the 
NPT, we cannot but make another choice. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

