<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. `Military Pressure', `Scheming' Rejected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. `Military Pressure', `Scheming' Rejected </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1606102494 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1007 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1606102494 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Military Pressure Cannot Be Justified"--KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, June 16 (KCNA) -- The United States is 
massing huge aggression forces around the Korean peninsula, 
scheming to impose "sanctions" upon the DPRK. Commenting on 
this, NODONG SINMUN in a by-lined article today says: 
  This eloquently proves that it does not want to truly solve 
the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula, but is trying to 
stifle the DPRK militarily on the pretext of the "nuclear 
development". 
  It is entirely wrong for the U.S. to put military pressure 
on 
the DPRK over the "nuclear issue". 
  The nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula cropped up when 
the 
U.S. deployed nuclear weapons in South Korea and resorted to 
nuclear threat against the North. The United States has turned 
South Korea into the largest nuclear base in the Far East, 
targeting its Asian strategy against the Korean peninsula. 
Owing to the nuclear war moves of the United States, South 
Korea has turned into a most dangerous hotbed of a nuclear war 
in the world and the Korean people have to live under a constant 
nuclear threat of the U.S. thus the United States gave rise to 
the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula and is gravely 
threatening the DPRK with nuclear weapons. Yet it is increasing 
military pressure on the DPRK over its "nuclear development". 
This is a shameless act which reminds us of a guilty party 
filing the suit first. 
  The DPRK's nuclear activities, in view of their peaceful 
nature, cannot be a pretext of pressure. Its nuclear activities 
are designed to solve the problem of energy badly needed for 
economic construction and the DPRK's atomic energy facilities 
strictly serve this purpose. There is nothing else in its 
nuclear activities. Nevertheless, the U.S. is putting military 
pressure on the DPRK on groundless charges. This tells that the 
United States has not yet given up the scheme to stifle Korean 
socialism with strength. 
  In view of the sincere efforts made by the DPRK till now for 
a solution to the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula, the 
U.S. military pressure cannot be justified. 
  For a peaceful and fair solution to the nuclear issue on the 
Korean peninsula, we have consistently called for dialogue and 
negotiation and made a signal overture for a package solution to 
the issue. 
  If the United States had come out to the third-round 
DPRK-U.S. talks and the nuclear issue had been solved in a 
package deal, the state would not have developed as now. 
  The DPRK's reactor core refueling cannot be a pretext of 
military pressure. 
  We urged the International Atomic Energy Agency five times 
to 
take measures needed for core refueling and notified the U.S. 
side that, if a package solution were achieved and the unique 
status of the DPRK removed, though belatedly, we could allow all 
the routine and ad hoc inspections including the selected 
preservation of fuel rods even in the course of core refueling. 
  Facts show that the failure to resolve the nuclear issue on 
the Korean peninsula is wholly attributable to the United States 
and some dishonest quarters of the IAEA secretariat. 
  The criminal attempt to stifle the DPRK under the pretext of 
the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula while blocking its 
solution can never be tolerated. 
  The Korean people who regard independence as their life and 
soul would decisively react, if the United States ventured a 
military provocation against the DPRK over the nuclear issue. 

</TEXT>

