<H3> <TI>   Voice of America Cited on Situation in Korea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Voice of America Cited on Situation in Korea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1606050694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0420 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1606050694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, June 16 (KCNA) -- Radio Voice of America 
Monday aired an article on the situation of the Korean peninsula. 
  The radio said that more than 40 years have passed since the 
Korean war ceased in July 1953, but huge Armed Forces of the 
belligerent parties are standing opposed to each other along the 
Military Demarcation Line on the Korean peninsula, with no peace 
agreement signed to completely end the state of war. 
  Noting that the international dispute over "full nuclear 
inspection" is facing the most grave crisis in which such a 
fabulous price as a second Korean war would have to be paid, the 
radio asked: Can the North Korean Army "be defeated" in this war? 
  Recalling that the United States has deployed Patriot 
missiles in South Korea and is reinforcing arms equipment of 
latest types and keeping the U.S. troops present in South Korea 
and the South Korean puppet army on the keen alert, the radio 
said: But we must remember that the Korean peninsula is not 
the Balkan peninsula and that, unlike Iraq, a vast desert area, 
80 percent of it is covered with mountains, and the North Korean 
Army the United States would deal with is a special army 
different from other adversaries in the past. 
  The radio said one must not forget that President Kim 
Il-song, the elder statesman who has dealt with the United 
States and Japan for a long time, and supreme commander of the 
Army Kim Chong-il lead the North Korean Armed Forces and people. 
  Noting that today the U.S. military is finding itself in the 
toughest spot over this problem, the radio said nobody has 
indicated a solution to it and days are going by in vexation. 

</TEXT>

