<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Media Urge South To Destroy `Wall' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Media Urge South To Destroy `Wall' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506124694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1105 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1506124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, June 15 (KCNA) -- Foreign newspapers 
strongly urged the United States and the South Korean 
authorities to pull down the concrete wall built by them in the 
area South of the Military Demarcation Line. 
  The Ghanaian paper GHANA TIMES said that the United States 
and the South Korean authorities have built the concrete wall 
for the purpose of perpetuating the division of Korea and 
blocking the people's movement for reunification. 
  The Dutch paper MANIFEST said that the South Korean 
authorities, instigated by the United States, have built the 
concrete wall under the pretext of preventing a fictitious 
"invasion from the North" and committed an anti-national crime 
to keep divided forever the Korean people who have lived as a 
homogeneous nation, boasting of the 5,000-year long history and 
brilliant culture. 
  The Indian magazine STUDENTS' FORUM said that with the 
concrete wall built the fellow countrymen in the North and the 
South are unable to freely come and go and inquire after the 
health of their families and relatives and overall opening in 
all realms of politics, the economy and culture between the 
North and the South is blocked. 
  The Peruvian paper LA REPUBLICA said that there is no wall 
in 
the area north of the Military Demarcation Line but wire 
entanglements marking the boundary line. It said that to pull 
down the concrete wall is the will of the Korean people and the 
requirement of the times and the preservation of the concrete 
wall is a shame of the nation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

