<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Carter Remarks on U.S.-DPRK Normalization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Carter Remarks on U.S.-DPRK Normalization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1606020994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0100 GMT 16 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1606020994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government decided to support the resolution 
calling for sanctions against the North which was drafted by the 
United States and which is being discussed among the UN Security 
Council member states, and to maintain close cooperation with 
friendly countries for the passage of the resolution through the 
United Nations. This decision was made at a meeting of the 
unification and security-related ministers after they were 
informed by the United States yesterday of the draft resolution 
on sanctions against the North. 
  In this connection, a responsible Foreign Ministry official 
said that ample discussion was held with our government prior to 
the U.S. draft of the resolution calling for sanctions against 
the North which stipulates an arms embargo and a one-month grace 
period and that it thus well reflects our government's position. 
  The Foreign Ministry official said that because former U.S. 
President Carter made clear in his remarks that North Korean 
nuclear transparency was the premise for normalization of 
U.S.-North Korean relations, this does not significantly deviate 
from the basic policy of the ROK and the United States to solve 
the North Korean nuclear problem thoroughly and comprehensively. 

</TEXT>

