<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry To Publicize War Documents From Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry To Publicize War Documents From Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106075094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0732 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1106075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 (YONHAP) -- The Foreign Ministry will 
make public parts of the Korean war (1950-1953) documents 
received from Russia on June 25, officials said Saturday. The 
documents are being translated into Korean by Foreign Ministry 
officials and staff at the South Korean Embassy in Russia, they 
said. 
  "The documents include telegraph messages between Kim 
Il-song 
and Joseph Stalin. They can substantially prove North Korea 
made the first provocation against South Korea," said one 
official, "Once the papers are translated, they will carry much, 
much value." North Korean still insists that Seoul made the 
first attack. 
  Russia gave South Korean President Kim Yong-sam the war 
documents when the latter visited Moscow last week. The bundle 
contains over 600 pages of over 200 items including 
communication North Korea had with the former Soviet Union and 
China from January 1949 to October 1950. For example, the 
materials show Kim Il-song requested Moscow's support for the 
war in January 1950 and Stalin agreed the following month. They 
include an attack plan prepared by Russian military officials in 
May 1950 and the kind of weapons Soviets supplied to North Korea 
between September 1949 and April 1950. 
  Officials said the original papers will be kept by the 
government and sensitive materials will be kept confidential. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

