Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruling Party Discusses DPRK With Ministers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ruling Party Discusses DPRK With Ministers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506021894 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0103 GMT 15 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1506021894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Democratic Liberal Party [DLP] urged the 
government to reconsider [chaegomto] the Joint Declaration on 
the Denuclearization of the Korean peninsula if 
non-implementation continues. 
  Some 250 lawmakers of the DLP and of district party chapters 
held a series of meetings today in presence of Foreign Minister 
Han Sung- chu and Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae to seek measures 
to actively cope with [nungdongjoguro taechohanun panganul 
mosaek] the North Korean nuclear issue that is becoming 
increasingly strained with each day [nallo kinbakhaejyo kago 
innun]. 
  While reading a report entitled "Our Party's Basic Position 
on the North Korean Nuclear Issue," the DLP lawmakers and 
chairmen of party chapters said that the North Korea's ambition 
[yayok] to develop nuclear weapons is a serious challenge 
[chungdaehan tojon] that threatens the peace and security of the 
Korean peninsula, and stressed that it can never be allowed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

