<F P=101> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: Plan To Woo Scientists `Ready' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official: Plan To Woo Scientists `Ready' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1606095394 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0605 GMT 16 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1606095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, June 16 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- The paper on 
proposals to attract foreign and Malaysian scientists and 
engineers working abroad to the country is ready and awaiting 
approval from the relevant government agencies, Science, 
Technology and Environment Minister Law Hieng Ding said Thursday. 
  He said the working committee, headed by his deputy, Peter 
Chin, had finalised the paper recently and was waiting for 
government agencies such as the Public Services Department and 
Treasury to endorse it before presenting it to the cabinet for 
final approval. 
  The scheme was meant to meet the country's needs for 
scientists and engineers to fulfil its plan to be an 
industrialised nation by the year 2020, he told reporters after 
opening an exhibition on the beauty of nature at the National 
Museum here. 
  Law said that the incentive package, among others, offered 
the target group salaries comparable to that offered by other 
countries with fringe benefits including permanent resident 
status, if necessary. 

</TEXT>

